ew of language. Rejecting the claim that critical legal studies can be seen as the heir of legal realism, Legal Realism Regained argues that, with respect to each of these three topics, the realists still present a stronger argument than their more radical descendants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLawxPhilosophy. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475659440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804787529?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804787529/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles